snippet.textDisplay:
@Peter Jacobsen Legal and political system..here in Singapore..is similar to British system.. because Singapore was an ex-British colony.
So..we have a Parliament.
As far as that goes.. that's about it.
In my eyes..a system is a mere system. For us commoners, it serves nothing to our livelihood if problems are not resolved.
Tell that to the homeless in USA..how does systems help them?
Every country in this world has a different set of unique problems..
Just as every family has..
Does what works in my family applicable to yours?
The idea of high morals and values superimposed on others..is to justify that every situation is the same..which is totally not reality.
Just because it worked for your family.. doesn't mean it will work for mine.
That's when your Western values got it wrong.
And the pandemic is one such questionable issue challenging your western system..
Is the right of the individual's choice more important than the harmful effects that rights give?
What if your rights caused the death of your neighbor?
Anti-Vax protest all over Europe.
Did you know Vaccination is Compulsory in Singapore? In general..without vaccination..you cannot eat anywhere but at home..
But in China.. it's not..
So.. China is more liberal ..right?
Did you know that in 2020 Singapore was strict..but last year, your Western countries became stricter than Singapore..in pandemic rules..
Yet China was kinda relaxed..
Chinese people were walking the streets without masks on..last year..

So..who is more freedom then?

Did you know in China ..there is a lot of talk in Weibo.. criticism of government..and it's allowed..or technically.. relaxed on..
I guess your Western media never told you that..

Here in Singapore..voting attendance is high because it is compulsory..
It's not in your country..right?
But your Democratic system simply gets a lot of political infighting here..as much as there is in your country..
Now..how does that help the people then?

Outcome..is what matters to us common folks..
If you spend your life in trouble because of a system..then the outcome is bad.
If the system improves your livelihood..then the system is good.
Today..in China..the population have seen their lives gone from poverty to wealth..
Imagine this..you see your life gone from poor to rich..you use to ride on bicycles to work..now you have a Tesla car.
Now..that is a system that works.

Now here..in Singapore..i have seen my country gone more and more expensive..
How does that help me?
Think about it!!!

snippet.textDisplay:
@Calvin Blue Democracy may not give leaders that you approve of, but it gives leaders that the majority of people approve of. And the beauty of democracy is that if people want to have a dictatorship instead, they can vote to end democracy. I don't think that has ever happened and I doubt it ever will. People like the power to decide their government.
If you think Singapore is stricter than China, you don't know China very well.

snippet.textDisplay: @Calvin Blue You raise some interesting questions. Nevertheless, Singapore has a legal and political system based largely on those in the west. That's just a fact. If the people in Singapore wish to change those systems to something more in line with what you prefer, you have a system of democratic elections which allows you to do that. Of course, you need to get at least 50% of Singaporeans to agree with you, and that might be difficult.

snippet.textDisplay:
The values we share include:
-Respect for the rights of the individual - individuals are at the center, rather than individuals just being tools of the state.
-Respect for private property
-The importance of institutions, such as independent courts and many other institutions that function independently of government.
-Freedom of expression
-Democracy, allowing the people to change the government if they are not satisfied.
These are some of the more important values we share.
